# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-cooling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with an annual household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low rate of air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow by between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona; Hong Kong; China; Japan; and Italy.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Costs of health care can act as another barrier: the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and has encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] The Chinese inventor Ding Huan (1st century CE) of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning.
[src:air-cooling/air-conditioning] In the nations of Europe where the technology is relatively unadopted, the strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:air-cooling/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:air-cooling/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:air-cooling/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:air-cooling/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:air-cooling/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The balance shaft was invented and patented by British engineer Frederick W.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] It is most commonly used in inline-four and V6 engines used in automobiles and motorcycles.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The operating principle of a balance shaft system is that two shafts carrying identical eccentric weights rotate in opposite directions at twice the engine speed.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The phasing of the shafts is such that the centrifugal forces produced by the weights cancel the vertical second-order forces (at twice the engine RPM) produced by the engine.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The horizontal forces produced by the balance shafts are equal and opposite, and so cancel each other.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The balance shafts do not reduce the vibrations experienced by the crankshaft.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Numerous motorcycle engines— particularly parallel-twin engines— have employed balance shaft systems, for example the Yamaha TRX850 and Yamaha TDM850 engines have a 270° crankshaft with a balance shaft.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] An alternative approach, as used by the BMW GS parallel-twin, is to use a 'dummy' connecting rod which moves a hinged counterweight.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Balance shafts are often used in inline-four engines, to reduce the second-order vibration (a vertical force oscillating at twice the engine RPM) that is inherent in the design of a typical inline-four engine.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The amount of vibration also increases with engine displacement, resulting in balance shafts often being used in inline-four engines with displacements of 2.2 L (134 cu in) or more.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Both an increased stroke or bore cause an increased secondary vibration; a larger stroke increases the difference in acceleration and a larger bore increases the mass of the pistons.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] The Lanchester design of balance shaft systems was refined with the Mitsubishi Astron 80, an inline-four car engine introduced in 1975.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] This engine was the first to locate one balance shaft higher than the other, to counteract the second order rolling couple (i.e. about the crankshaft axis) due to the torque exerted by the inertia caused by increases and decreases in engine speed.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] In a flat-four engine, the forces are cancelled out by the pistons moving in opposite directions.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Therefore balance shafts are not needed in flat-four engines.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Balance shafts are also used in straight-five engines such as GM Vortec 3700.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] In a straight-six engine and flat-six engine, the rocking forces are naturally balanced out, therefore balance shafts are not required.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] V6 engines are inherently unbalanced, regardless of the V-angle.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Any inline engine with an odd number of cylinders has a primary imbalance, which causes an end-to-end rocking motion.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] As each cylinder bank in a V6 has three cylinders, each cylinder bank experiences this motion.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Balance shaft(s) are used on various V6 engines to reduce this rocking motion.
[src:air-cooling/balance-shaft] Examples are the Mercedes-Benz OM629 and Volvo B8444S engine.
